    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-11-01T14:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-11-01T14:00:00-05:00" n="834"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d834">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.7490F/11–144: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gallman</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-11-01T20:00:00+01:00"
                            >November 1, 1944—8 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received November 2—12:55 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>9453. The Embassy took up with the Foreign Office the contents of the
                    Department’s 8924 October 26, 2 p.m. Foreign Office tells us that the
                    Departmental Committee on Censorship in London on which Lt. Commander Patterson,
                    United States Navy, is a representative objected to the establishment of a Saudi
                    Arabian Government radio station on security grounds because the control of the
                    station would be in the hands of the Saudi Arabian Government. The Foreign
                    Office also stated that Mr. Berle<note n="99" xml:id="d834fn99">Adolf A. Berle,
                        Jr., Assistant Secretary of State.</note> had discussed this matter with the
                    British Embassy in Washington and that the Foreign Office would prefer that this
                    whole question be handled through that channel.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gallman</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
